          "subtitle": "When Sensors Lie, AI Follows",
          "slidecontent": "• Sensors detect speed, distance, obstacles\n• Faulty data enters AI instantly\n• AI trusts sensors, not reality\n• Bad input causes bad decisions\n• Weather and dirt cause errors"
        },
        {
          "number": 5,
          "slidetitle": "Sensor Failures and Misreadings",
          "subtitle": "When Sensors Lie, AI Follows",
          "slidecontent": "• Sensors feed AI systems real-time data about speed, obstacles, and surroundings\n• Dirty, damaged, or poorly positioned sensors can send false readings\n• AI treats bad data as truth\n• A blocked lidar sensor on an autonomous vehicle may fail to detect a pedestrian crossing the road\n• Adverse weather like heavy rain or fog can degrade sensor accuracy significantly\n• No built-in scepticism means the AI acts on whatever the sensor reports, right or wrong"
        },
        {
          "number": 6,
          "slidetitle": "Sensor Failures and Misclassification",
          "subtitle": "When Sensors Mislead AI Systems",
          "slidecontent": "• Sensors like cameras, radar, and lidar feed AI systems the raw data they need to make decisions\n\n• Dirt, rain, or glare can corrupt sensor readings\n\n• A misclassified object (a pedestrian read as a static obstacle, for example) can trigger the wrong response entirely\n\n• Sensor fusion, combining multiple sensor types, reduces but does not eliminate this risk\n\n• Real incidents have shown AI systems failing to detect vehicles in unusual orientations or poor lighting conditions\n\n• Even brief, partial sensor failures can cascade into serious safety events"
        },
        {
          "number": 7,
          "slidetitle": "Lessons From Real Failures",
          "subtitle": "What past incidents teach us today",
          "slidecontent": "• The 2009 Air France 447 crash showed how automation confusion can overwhelm even trained crews under pressure\n• Sensor failures matter\n• Therac-25, a radiation therapy machine, killed patients when a software race condition removed its safety checks\n• Over-reliance on automated alerts caused the 2018 Boeing 737 MAX MCAS system to override pilot inputs repeatedly\n• Small software bugs in safety-critical systems can cascade into catastrophic, irreversible outcomes\n• Real incidents share a common thread, which is that human oversight was reduced just when it was needed most"
        },
        {
          "number": 8,
